investigation.title: Modeling cellular responses to serum and vitamin D in microgravity using a human kidney microphysiological system
investigation.description: The microgravity environment aboard the International Space Station (ISS) provides a unique stressor that can help understand underlying cellular and molecular drivers of pathological changes observed in astronauts with the ultimate goals of developing strategies to enable long- term spaceflight and better treatment of diseases on Earth. We used this unique environment to evaluate the effects of microgravity on kidney proximal tubule epithelial cell (PTEC) response to serum exposure and vitaminD biotransformation capacity.

project.funding: These studies were supported by funding from the National Center for Advancing Translational Sciences (UG3TR002178 and UG3TR002158), The International Space Station U.S. National Laboratory, and an unrestricted gift from the Northwest Kidney Centers to the Kidney Research Institute.
